In Reply:<br>
     In regards to war atrocities, let's understand that no one is immune, and no war is spared.  In every single war, there is always someone who carries the conduct and mission too far.  War by nature is one great atrocity, a failure of diplomatic mission, a claimer of lives, most of which (soldiers included) are not connected to its causes and benefit the least.<br>
     My main question is what is a atrocity?  I believe that soldiers can't be held to the same standards of behavior as our general society.  How can they?  The plain and simple purpose of the military is to kill and destroy, actions considered morally wrong in society, but rewarded in military service.<br>
     All war is killing!  Is it a atrocity, when a person kills without question?  That's a survival skill.  Is it killing non-combatants?  In Vietnam, such as at My Lai, that is the case.  Cally was very wrong, and deserved a worst sentence than what he got, but was it him totally or a vague military mission policy against a ememy who often hid amongst the civilain population.  I am not downplaying the cruel actions of certain individuals in Vietnam, but such actions were the exception more than the rule.  According to the Vietnam War Almanac by Col Harry G. Summers (Facts on File, 1985), only 201 Army personnel and 77 Marines were court-martialed for serious crimes in Vietnam (1965-1973).  Also, how about the terrorist practices of the NVA/VC that were used sometimes against fellow Vietnamese.<br>
     Take World War II for example.  America fire bombed the Germany cities of Dresden and Hamburg, killing hundreds of thousands of civilians in a hellish firestorm.  Was that a atrocity?  Certainly seems like it, but the men were following orders of the high command.  (Besides, I knew some men who did these missions, some are relatives, all are kind men).  My point is that soldiers can't be judged by normal standards of society.  Art Varinelli has a great quote to that effect on his websight.<br>
My question to all is what are the standards used to judge soldiers, when their job may involve killing?  <br><br>
I speak with all sincerety on this subject, as a son of a Vietnam vet.  My dad who worked on civil action construction programs with the Vietnamese and trained their soldiers.  I pose the question for further discussion with the hopes it can be discussed in a civil fashion, for most of all I seek to understand as a 23 year old guy, who didn't live through Vietnam.
